frican-American children—as a springboard to ask fundamental questions about the practice and future of public health. Lead Wars chronicles the obstacles faced by public health workers in the conservative, pro-business, anti-regulatory climate that took off in the Reagan years and that stymied efforts to eliminate lead from the environments and the bodies of American children.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aLead poisoning in childrenxPreventionxGovernment policyzUnited States. 0aLead poisoning in childrenzUnited States. 0aLead poisoningzUnited StatesxHistory. 7aMEDICAL / Health Policy.2bisacsh  a20th century.  aamerica.  aamerican children.  achronic illness.  aenvironmental sciences.  aepidemiology.  aexperiments.  ahealth and wellness.  ahealth policies.  ahistorical.  ahuman condition.  alead poisoning.  alegal conflicts.  anonfiction.  apoisoning epidemic.  apolitical.  apolitics of science.  apublic health agencies.  apublic health workers.  apublic health.  areagan administration.  aretrospective.  asocial historians.  atoxic exposure.  aunethical research.  aus history.1 aHooker Odom, Carmen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMilbank, Samuel L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRosner, David, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052027325240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095495340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520954953423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520954953/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YU